@NODE "What" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - What Is A FileNote?"

@{B}@{U}What Is A FileNote?@{UU} All AmigaDOS Versions@{UB}

A @{B}FILE NOTE@{UB} (sometimes called a COMMENT) is a bit of text that the user can
add to a file or directory to remind him/herself of something about the
file, or that the creator of the file can add to tell the user something
about it.

The file note is @{B}NOT@{UB} a part of the file itself and @{B}cannot@{UB} be seen when
the file is examined in any way such as loading text into a text reader.
It is written to the @{"header block" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/HeaderBlock"}.

The FileNote can be examined with the @{"LIST" LINK "ADB:Parts_11-20/13.List/MAIN"}. For example:-

  > LIST DF1:MyFile
    --> MyFile                       514 ----rwed 01-Apr-96 23:10:13
        : this is a FileNote attached to MyFile

The FileNote is shown on the second line after the colon (:).

File notes or comments can also be shown by:-

- Opening file icon's @{"Information Window" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/Info_Window"}
  It is in the text gadget labelled "COMMENT".

- Using other programs such as @{"directory utilities" LINK "ADB:Misc/Glossary/DirUtility"}.


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - Usage"

@{B}@{U}The Filenote Usage@{UU} All AmigaDOS Versions@{UB}

FILENOTE can be used in one of these ways:-

  FILENOTE FileName

  FILENOTE FileName FileNote

  FILENOTE FileName FileNote OPTION

where OPTION can be one of:-

  @{" ALL   " LINK "All"} Version 2.0 Onwards@{UB}
  @{" QUIET " LINK "Quiet"} Version 2.0 Onwards

FILENOTE used with only a file name (first usage above) will @{"remove" LINK "Removing"} a
FileNote from a file.

The most common usage is the second:-

  FILENOTE FileName FileNote

If the file is not in the current directory then you should include the
path to the file.

If there are spaces in the FileNote then it @{B}must@{UB} be enclosed in inverted
commas.

The FileNote has a maximum length of 79 characters.

For example:-

  > FILENOTE s:startup-sequence "This is my special startup sequence file"

If you now entered:-

  > LIST s:startup-sequence

you would see something like:-

  startup-sequence 2296 ----rw-d 04-Jun-94 13:06:38
  : This is my special startup sequence file


