@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Pattern" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - Pattern Matching"

@{B}@{U}Pattern Matching On File Names@{UU} Version 2.0 Onwards@{UB}

A @{B}pattern@{UB} can be used to add the same file note to a number of files.
For example:-

  FILENOTE Documents:Letters/To_Mum#? "These are my letters to Mum"

This would add the FileNote to all file names starting with "To_Mum" that
are in the directory "Letters" on the disk "Documents".


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "All" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - The ALL Option"

@{B}@{U}The ALL Option@{UU} Version 2.0 Onwards@{UB}

The @{B}ALL@{UB} option, when used on a directory name instead of a file name,
will add the FileNote to:-

- the directory itself
- all files in the directory
- any sub-directories in the directory
- all files in all sub-directories

For example:-

  FILENOTE Sys:Devs "This FileNote goes to everything in devs"

This would add the FileNote to all files in "Devs" and to all sub-directories
and their files such as the "Keymaps" and "Printers" sub-directories.

When you use a file pattern or the ALL option, a list is given in the
window of all directory and file names that have the FileNote added to them.


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Quiet" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - The QUIET Option"

@{B}@{U}The QUIET Option@{UU} Version 2.0 Onwards@{UB}

The @{B}QUIET@{UB} option will suppress the output that would otherwise appear
with patterns and ALL. For example:-


  FILENOTE Documents:Letters/To_Mum#? "These are my letters to Mum" QUIET
  FILENOTE Sys:Devs "this FileNote goes to everything in devs" QUIET


@{JCENTER}=== End of Text ===
@{JLEFT}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Removing" "Part 61 - The FILENOTE Command - Removing a FileNote"

@{B}@{U}Removing a FileNote From a File@{UB}@{UU}

If you use FILENOTE as follows:-

  FILENOTE FileName

then any FileNotes previously attached to the file will be removed.

Actually, as there is no string after the file name, a FileNote is attached
that is 0 bytes long!

@{B}AmigaDOS v1.x note@{UB} - you cannot use it as shown above. You  must use:-

  FILENOTE FileName ""

The two inverted commas with nothing between them, not even a space,
represents a string of 0 bytes.


